In Week 36, the pattern that had been forming for months came into sharp relief. The presidency was no longer merely leaning on institutions; it was reaching inside them, rearranging their wiring so that law, security, and information bent toward one man\'92s grievances and fears. The week\'92s events did not bring a single spectacular rupture. Instead, they showed how a democracy can be hollowed from within while its outer shell still stands. Courts still sit, elections still occur, agencies still issue rules. Yet the purposes those institutions serve are altered. Power is used less as a trust and more as a weapon. The Democracy Clock held at 7:58 p.m. in public terms, but the internal movement told a different story. The hands did not lurch forward, yet the gears that drive them slipped further out of alignment.\
