At the close of the prior period, the Clock stood at 7:58 p.m. It remains there now, though the underlying measure crept forward by a tenth of a minute. That small numerical change masks the depth of the week\'92s shifts. The time did not move because the system collapsed; it moved because the system adapted to a more openly retaliatory presidency. Law was used more aggressively against critics and more gently toward allies. The civil service was treated less as a neutral workforce and more as a pool of loyalists and expendables. Economic and statistical tools were turned toward obscuring hardship and rewarding friends. At the same time, some courts, state governments, and legislators pushed back, slowing but not stopping the drift. The net effect was not a dramatic fall but a tightening of the vise: more pressure on dissent, more impunity for insiders, and less room for truth to stand on its own.\
\
The clearest line of movement ran through the justice system. The week opened with the story of Tom Homan, Trump\'92s \'93border czar,\'94 whose recorded acceptance of $50,000 in cash from undercover FBI agents had once been the core of a bribery case. Under Trump\'92s second term, that case was not merely closed; it was denounced by political appointees as a \'93deep state\'94 plot, and the FBI and Justice Department leadership declared there was \'93no credible evidence of criminal wrongdoing\'94 despite the tape. Democrats in Congress tried to pry the matter open again, writing to watchdogs and demanding tax records, but they did so without subpoena power and against a Justice Department whose Public Integrity Section had been gutted from thirty-six lawyers to two. In a healthy system, such a case would test whether law applies equally to powerful insiders. In this system, it became a test of loyalty, and the answer was clear. Allies would be shielded, and those who pressed too hard would find doors closed.\
