At the same time, the machinery of prosecution was turned against long-standing critics of the president. Erik Siebert, the acting U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of Virginia, had reviewed evidence against New York Attorney General Letitia James and former FBI Director James Comey and concluded there was no case. For that, he was first pressured to resign and then, by Trump\'92s own account, fired. In his place, the president installed Lindsey Halligan, a former personal lawyer with no prosecutorial experience, first as interim and then as nominee for a full term. Within days, Halligan\'92s office secured a grand jury indictment of Comey on charges of lying to Congress and obstructing a proceeding\'97charges that career prosecutors had previously declined to bring and that many legal observers considered thin. The indictment did not just target one man. It sent a message to the entire law enforcement and intelligence community that crossing the president in the past could carry criminal consequences in the present.\
\
The pattern extended beyond Comey. The FBI searched the home and office of John Bolton, another prominent critic, over alleged mishandling of classified documents, even as Bolton\'92s lawyer insisted the materials had been declassified. The administration opened a criminal investigation into former CIA Director John Brennan for his role in the 2016 assessment of Russian interference. A senior Justice Department official instructed U.S. attorneys to draw up plans to investigate a Soros-funded group after Trump demanded action against the billionaire. In each case, the targets shared a common trait: they had challenged Trump\'92s power or narrative. The law, which in theory should limit the executive, was instead being used as an extension of his will. The trait the Clock tracks as \'93law is a weapon, not a limit\'94 deepened its presence, not through a single decree but through a week\'92s worth of aligned choices.\
\
Courts, which might have served as a counterweight, offered a mixed picture. On one front, they checked executive overreach. A federal judge ordered the restoration of $500 million in frozen grants to UCLA, rejecting what appeared to be a politically motivated punishment over alleged civil-rights violations. Another judge blocked the administration from withholding billions in emergency management grants from states that refused to cooperate with federal immigration enforcement, calling the conditions unconstitutional and arbitrary. These rulings affirmed that some judges still saw their role as enforcing neutral rules against the executive, even when the stakes were high. They mattered. They also stood out as exceptions.\
