The Supreme Court\'92s emergency orders told a different story. In Trump v. Slaughter, the Court granted a stay that kept Rebecca Slaughter, a Democratic Federal Trade Commission commissioner found to have been illegally fired, out of her job while the case proceeds. The decision, by a 6\'963 vote, signaled deference to the president\'92s claimed power to remove leaders of independent agencies, tilting the balance toward executive control over regulators meant to stand apart from politics. In another case, Department of State v. AIDS Vaccine Advocacy Coalition, the Court allowed Trump\'92s Executive Order 14169 to stand while litigation continues, clearing the way for the administration to withhold $4 billion in foreign aid that Congress had already appropriated. Together, these orders strengthened the presidency\'92s hand over both domestic regulation and international spending, even as lower courts tried to hold the line elsewhere. The trait that measures whether courts rule for donors and elites edged upward, not because judges declared it so, but because their emergency choices made it easier for the executive to bend independent bodies to his purposes.\
