If law was being reshaped, so too was the civil service that carries it out. The week brought a blunt directive from the Office of Management and Budget: in the event of a government shutdown, agencies were to prepare not for temporary furloughs, as in past standoffs, but for large-scale firings of workers whose programs did not align with the president\'92s priorities. OMB Director Russell Vought made clear that this was not just about saving money; it was about using the shutdown threat to reorder the federal workforce along ideological lines. At the same time, the administration signaled that it expected a shutdown and saw it as a way to hit Democratic constituencies hardest. The message to career officials was stark. Their job security no longer depended on neutral performance but on political usefulness. That is a different kind of government.\
\
Elsewhere, agencies were being repurposed from their statutory missions toward ideological goals. At the Department of Housing and Urban Development, whistleblowers described how the Office of Fair Housing had been downsized, staff reassigned or laid off, and gag orders imposed. Cases involving discrimination against domestic violence victims were dropped or altered under political pressure, and settlements shrank. The effect was to hollow out federal enforcement of the Fair Housing Act, particularly in cases that touched on race and gender. At the State Department, staff reported that more than half of ambassadorships were vacant and that new \'93fidelity\'94 metrics measured loyalty in ways that could affect promotions and job security. In immigration, the administration began recruiting military lawyers from the Judge Advocate General\'92s corps to serve as temporary immigration judges, blurring the line between civilian adjudication and military discipline in a system already under strain from a mass deportation push. These moves did not abolish the civil service; they bent it, making it more responsive to partisan direction and less anchored in professional norms.\
\
Immigration enforcement became a central theater where these shifts played out. Congress passed a bill allocating $170 billion to Immigration and Customs Enforcement over four years, with the explicit goal of deporting one million immigrants annually. This vast funding increase, coupled with the recruitment of JAG officers as immigration judges, signaled a structural commitment to high-volume removals. Newly released data showed that, for the first time in Trump\'92s second term, ICE was detaining more immigrants with no criminal record than those with one, contradicting the administration\'92s claim that it was focused on \'93bad hombres.\'94 The human cost of this approach surfaced in individual stories. Rodney Taylor, a double amputee from Liberia, was held for eight months in Georgia\'92s Stewart detention center despite serious medical needs. Ismael Ayala-Uribe, a Mexican man, died after being transferred from an ICE facility to a hospital in California. Ian Roberts, the superintendent of Des Moines public schools, was detained on a final removal order despite his role as a widely respected local leader. These were not abstractions. They were lives caught in a system that now treated status and identity as grounds for punishment.\
