Inside the detention system, nineteen detainees at an ICE facility within Louisiana\'92s Angola prison launched a hunger strike, demanding basic medical care, necessities, and access to legal and religious services. Their protest drew attention to conditions described as unsafe and degrading. In Dallas, a gunman opened fire on an ICE field office from a nearby rooftop, killing one detainee and injuring two others before taking his own life. Shell casings and notes with anti-ICE messages were found, and the FBI treated the attack as targeted violence. The administration seized on such incidents to frame opposition to its immigration policies as a security threat. That framing would soon be codified in orders that reached far beyond the immigration system itself. The trait that tracks citizenship being stratified by wealth, ideology, and heritage moved higher, as enforcement patterns and funding choices deepened a tiered system of rights.\
