The week\'92s most consequential documents were two pieces of paper signed at the White House. The first was an executive order designating \'93antifa\'94 as a domestic terrorist organization. Though antifa is more a loose tendency than a structured group, the order described it as a militarist, anarchist enterprise seeking to overthrow the government and directed agencies to investigate, disrupt, and dismantle its \'93operations,\'94 including those who fund them. Legal experts noted that U.S. law provides no clear framework for labeling domestic groups as terrorist organizations, precisely because of First Amendment concerns. Nonetheless, the order opened the door to using counterterrorism tools\'97surveillance, asset freezes, enhanced penalties\'97against people associated, however loosely, with left-leaning protest. It marked a shift from seeing protest as a political act to seeing it as a security problem.\
