The second document was a presidential memorandum on domestic terrorism and political violence. Issued on September 25, it instructed the FBI\'92s joint terrorism taskforces, the Justice Department, and the Treasury to focus on what Trump called a radical leftwing \'93terror network\'94 fueling violence against ICE agents. It also directed the IRS to scrutinize tax-exempt entities that might be financing such activities. Civil liberties groups warned that the memo could be used to target nonprofits, activists, and community organizations that opposed administration policies, labeling them as security threats rather than political actors. Taken together, the order and the memo did more than respond to specific incidents. They reframed dissent itself\'97especially on the left\'97as a form of domestic terrorism, and they gave legal cover to treat protest, organizing, and even charitable work as potential crimes. The trait that tracks dissent being recast as disorder, treason, or terrorism rose sharply.\
