This reframing did not occur in a vacuum. It was reinforced by rhetoric from elected officials and by the selective use of violence as a political talking point. In Arizona, state representative John Gillette posted that Representative Pramila Jayapal should be \'93tried, convicted and hanged\'94 for a video in which she discussed non-violent protests against the administration. Gillette had previously defended January 6 rioters and made derogatory remarks about Muslims. His call for execution did not carry legal force, but it showed how far the language of treason and punishment had seeped into mainstream politics. At the same time, shootings at ICE facilities and threats against law enforcement were highlighted as evidence of a leftwing terror wave, even as the administration\'92s own words and policies stoked anger and fear. The trait that tracks dissenters being labeled unpatriotic, subversive, or corrupt also moved upward, as calls for extreme punishment of critics became more normalized.\
