Information and media, which might have countered these narratives, came under heavy pressure. At the Pentagon, Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth\'92s department issued a memo requiring journalists to sign a pledge not to gather or report \'93unauthorized\'94 information, even if unclassified, on pain of losing their press credentials. Reporters\'92 movements inside the building were restricted to specific areas, and escorts became mandatory. The stated justification was national security, but the effect was to make independent reporting on military affairs more difficult and to force journalists into a relationship of permission rather than scrutiny. The Pentagon\'92s move was echoed by the Federal Communications Commission, where Trump loyalist Brendan Carr threatened to revoke ABC affiliates\'92 broadcast licenses after late-night host Jimmy Kimmel criticized the administration\'92s response to the killing of Charlie Kirk. ABC suspended Kimmel\'92s show under that pressure, prompting public backlash, boycotts, and protests. After \'93days of thoughtful conversations,\'94 the network reinstated him, but major station groups Sinclair and Nexstar refused to air the program on their ABC affiliates. Independent media were squeezed while aligned outlets held the gate.\
