Truth itself was strained in other domains. In public remarks and at the United Nations, Trump claimed that acetaminophen use in pregnancy caused a \'93very increased risk of autism,\'94 despite decades of evidence to the contrary. He discouraged vaccines and promoted \'93natural\'94 motherhood, undermining trust in medical guidance. Former President Barack Obama called these statements \'93violence against the truth,\'94 and health officials in the United Kingdom urged women to ignore them. At the UN General Assembly, Trump delivered a 55-minute speech attacking green energy, calling climate change a \'93con job,\'94 and falsely claiming that London was moving toward sharia law. He urged nations to close their borders and expel foreigners, accused the UN of promoting a \'93globalist migration agenda,\'94 and boasted of ending wars and securing investments that independent fact-checkers said did not exist. His Treasury Secretary suggested that threats to European cities did not equate to threats to American cities, casting doubt on U.S. commitment to NATO. In parallel, the Energy Department announced it would return $13 billion in green project funds to the Treasury, dismissing prior climate initiatives as a \'93Green New Scam.\'94 The combination of falsehood and policy rollback did not just change the country\'92s stance on climate and migration; it rewrote the story the government tells about its responsibilities to the planet and to allies.\
