The manipulation of information extended to economic data and archives. The Bureau of Labor Statistics postponed its annual consumer expenditures report, a key tool for understanding inflation, shortly after Trump fired the BLS commissioner over disappointing job numbers. The U.S. Department of Agriculture terminated its long-running annual report on household food security, even though the last report had shown 18 million households facing food insecurity. USDA officials called the reports \'93redundant, costly, politicized and extraneous.\'94 At the same time, the department canceled a national food insecurity survey and froze more than $10 million in food assistance to Kansas after the state refused to hand over personal data on beneficiaries. These moves made it harder for state and local officials to assess hunger and for the public to gauge the real cost of inflation and labor market shifts. They also showed how data could be used as leverage: withheld from the public, demanded from states, and deployed to punish those who did not comply. The trait that tracks economic data being selectively published, massaged, or ignored rose sharply.\
