The National Archives, an institution meant to stand above politics, stumbled into the fray. A branch of the Archives released nearly unredacted military records of Representative Mikie Sherrill to an ally of her Republican opponent in the New Jersey governor\'92s race, including sensitive personal information. The release appeared to violate the Privacy Act and raised questions about whether archival processes were being politicized. At the same time, the Archives invited public comment on proposed records schedules, a routine but important step in deciding which federal records are preserved and which are destroyed. The juxtaposition was striking. On one hand, a formal process for public input on the fate of records; on the other, an improper disclosure that suggested those records could be weaponized in electoral contests. The trait that tracks whether government archives are sealed, sanitized, or misused edged higher, not because boxes were burned, but because the trust that underpins archival neutrality was shaken.\
