Economic power, too, was used in ways that blurred public purpose and private gain. The State Department announced plans to redirect $1.8 billion in foreign aid toward \'93America First\'94 projects, moving away from long-standing bipartisan goals of promoting democracy and health. The Treasury and other agencies prepared a $20 billion support package for Argentina\'92s right-wing president, Javier Milei, a Trump ally, outside the usual appropriations process. The Treasury also sanctioned the wife of a Brazilian Supreme Court justice who had overseen Jair Bolsonaro\'92s prosecution, prompting Brazil to accuse the U.S. of undue interference. Domestically, Trump imposed steep tariffs on Brazilian goods, pharmaceuticals, furniture, cabinets, and heavy trucks, often citing grievances tied to foreign prosecutions or trade practices. He promised to use tariff revenues to bail out American farmers hurt by his own trade policies. Meanwhile, Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem expedited $11 million in disaster aid to rebuild a historic pier in Naples, Florida, after intervention by a political donor. Each decision could be defended on narrow grounds. Together, they showed a pattern: foreign aid, sanctions, tariffs, and disaster relief were being steered toward allies and donors, and away from neutral criteria, making crony capitalism harder to distinguish from governance.\
