Amid these shifts, there were pockets of resistance and adaptation. In the realm of public health, seven Northeastern states and New York City formed a regional collaborative to coordinate vaccine guidance and emergency preparedness as federal recommendations grew more erratic. On the West Coast, governors of Oregon, Washington, California, and Hawaii issued their own winter vaccine recommendations, urging residents to stay current on Covid, flu, and RSV shots. AHIP, a major health insurance trade group, announced that its members would continue to cover all immunizations recommended by the federal Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices as of early September, even as national guidance wavered. These regional and private actions did not repair federal damage, but they showed how subnational actors could step into the vacuum, building parallel structures of trust and information. They kept some channels of truth open.\
