In elections and representation, the week brought both strain and modest reinforcement. In Georgia, the state Republican Party barred Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger from qualifying as a Republican candidate and expelled former Lieutenant Governor Geoff Duncan, punishing them for rejecting Trump\'92s false claims about the 2020 election. Raffensperger nonetheless announced a run for governor, pledging fidelity to law and the constitution, while Duncan switched parties and entered the race as a Democrat, arguing for cross-party coalitions against extremism. Their candidacies underscored how loyalty tests within a party can narrow internal democracy, even as voters retain formal choices on the ballot. In Arizona, Adelita Grijalva won a special election to fill her late father\'92s House seat, becoming the state\'92s first Latina member of Congress. Her victory narrowed the Republican majority and provided the final signature needed on a discharge petition to force a floor vote on releasing government files related to Jeffrey Epstein. That petition, backed by members from both parties, challenged leadership efforts to bury records that might implicate powerful figures, including Trump and prominent donors. It was a small but concrete step toward transparency in a domain where impunity has long been the norm.\
