What lies ahead is already partly visible. The executive order labeling antifa as a domestic terrorist organization and the domestic terrorism memorandum are not one-week stories; they will shape how law enforcement, the IRS, and the Treasury treat protests and nonprofits in the months to come. The Supreme Court\'92s stays in the Slaughter and foreign aid cases will influence how far the president can go in removing independent regulators and redirecting congressionally appropriated funds. The OMB memo on mass firings in a shutdown, and the administration\'92s stated expectation that a shutdown will occur and hit Democratic constituencies hardest, set the stage for a confrontation in which the livelihoods of civil servants become bargaining chips. The lawsuits against six states for voter data, and earlier suits against Maine and Oregon, will test how much control states retain over their rolls and how far the federal government can go in centralizing voter information. And the improper release of Mikie Sherrill\'92s records, if not treated as an aberration, could signal a broader pattern of using archives as tools in electoral combat.\
