By the end of Week 36, the Democracy Clock still read 7:58 p.m., but the meaning of that hour had shifted. The week did not bring tanks to the streets or the cancellation of elections. It brought something subtler and, in some ways, more insidious: the normalization of practices that treat law as a cudgel, civil servants as pawns, data as propaganda, and dissent as terrorism. The moral floor, already cracked, showed deeper fractures across character, ethics, restraint, truthfulness, good faith, and stewardship. Yet the story is not one of unbroken descent. Courts blocked some overreaches. States formed health alliances. Legislators pressed for Epstein files and Homan tapes. Voters in Arizona sent a representative to Congress who pledged to uphold democracy and protect immigrants\'92 rights. These acts did not reverse the week\'92s damage, but they kept alive the idea that institutions can still serve the public rather than the powerful.\
